# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: george-w-melville
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:george-w-melville/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The **First Soviet Antarctic Expedition** was a 1955–1957 expedition to Antarctica by explorers from the Soviet Union, led by Mikhail Somov.
[src:george-w-melville/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The principal task of the expedition was to organise the main base, Mirny, and perform limited scientific observations.
[src:george-w-melville/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] Other tasks were reconnaissance of sites for the inland bases Vostok and Sovetskaya; and oceanography of the Indian Ocean.
[src:george-w-melville/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The expedition lasted from 30 November 1955 to 1957, and involved 127 expedition members and 75 crew members.
[src:george-w-melville/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] It was led by Mikhail Somov, while his scientific deputy was V.
[src:george-w-melville/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] Suzyumov; also spelt Yevgeny or Eugene Suzyumov) was the scientific secretary of the expedition.
[src:george-w-melville/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] He later organised and participated in many other research expeditions to the Arctic, Antarctic, Atlantic, Indian, and Pacific Oceans, as well as authoring 13 popular science and history books, and many articles about the war in the Arctic and oceanographic studies.
[src:george-w-melville/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] He was the recipient of seven awards and 14 medals.
[src:george-w-melville/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] At a special meeting of the Soviet Geographical Society in October 1958 which paid tribute to the memory of Australian geologist and Antarctic explorer Douglas Mawson, Suzyumov said that Mawson had developed friendships with Soviet Antarctic explorers in his later years.
[src:george-w-melville/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] Suzyumov later wrote *Zhizn, otdannaia Antarktide*, translated as *A life given to the Antarctic: Douglas Mawson – Antarctic explorer*, published in 1968.
[src:george-w-melville/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] Three diesel-electric ships were used to transport the expedition.
[src:george-w-melville/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The final ship was used only for transporting perishables.
[src:george-w-melville/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] *Ob* and *Lena* were icebreakers 130m long and displacing 12,600 tons.
[src:george-w-melville/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] On 30 November 1955 *Ob* left port at Kaliningrad.
[src:george-w-melville/2nd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The **Second Soviet Antarctic Expedition** was led by Aleksei Treshnikov on the continent; the marine expedition on the "Ob" was led by I.
[src:george-w-melville/2nd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The "Ob" left Kaliningrad on 7 November, 1956.
[src:george-w-melville/2nd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] Three ships were used to transport the expedition, all diesel-electric.
[src:george-w-melville/2nd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The two main ships were as for the first expedition: RV *Ob* (flagship; captain I.
[src:george-w-melville/2nd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The third ship was *Kooperatsiya* (captain A.
[src:george-w-melville/2nd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] Yantselevich), used mainly as a transport vessel.
[src:george-w-melville/2nd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] Full scale scientific work for the International Geophysical Year (IGY) This included glacier mapping and wildlife tracking, among other things.
[src:george-w-melville/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The **Third Soviet Antarctic Expedition** (1957–59) was led by Yevgeny Tolstikov on the continent and included Czech future astronomer Antonín Mrkos; the marine expedition on the *Ob* was led by I V Maksimov.
[src:george-w-melville/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] Two diesel-electric ships were used to transport the expedition.
[src:george-w-melville/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] Man) and *Kooperatsiya* (captain A S Yantselevich), used mainly as a transport vessel.
[src:george-w-melville/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The ships arrived in Antarctica in November – December 1957.
[src:george-w-melville/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] Together with the ships' crews the expedition consisted of 445 men, of whom 183 were scheduled for wintering.
[src:george-w-melville/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The programme included 6 stations: (Mirny; Vostok; Sovetskaya; Oasis; Pionerskaya and Komsomol'skaya).
[src:george-w-melville/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The first tractor-train to the interior left on 26 December, with 32 men.
[src:george-w-melville/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] On 2 January 1958 the train arrived at Pionerskaya, and left again on the 8th.
[src:george-w-melville/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] On the 17th they reached Komsomol'skaya; conditions of travel were difficult.
[src:george-w-melville/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] A portion of the train (7 tractors and sledges) left on the 20th to relieve Vostok, arriving on the 27th, and delivering over 100 tons of cargo.
[src:george-w-melville/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] On the 28th the train left for Komsomol'skaya, arriving on the 31st.
[src:george-w-melville/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] On 3 February the train, with 27 men, left to found Sovetskaya; they reached 78° 24′ S, 87° 35′ E on the 10th, at an altitude of 3570 m.
[src:george-w-melville/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The station was rapidly constructed, and the train left on the 18th, returning to Mirny on 4 March, having completed a round trip of 4,000 km (2,500 mi).
[src:george-w-melville/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] After spending the Antarctic winter at Mirny, the Expedition undertook a second set of tractor traverses starting in September 1958.
[src:george-w-melville/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] One team reached the pole of inaccessibility and established The Pole of Inaccessibility station there on 14 December.
[src:george-w-melville/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] Estonian writer Juhan Smuul took part of the expedition as a Soviet journalist and described the interesting details in his 1960 book "Antarctica Ahoy!: The Ice Book" ("Jäine raamat" in Estonian).
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] The ship was recorded as *Bellaventure* until at least 1920.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] By 1927 she had been renamed *Александр Сибиряков*.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] In the Latin alphabet her name was rendered ***Alexander Sibiriakov*** until at least 1935.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] This had been changed to *Alexander Sibiryakov* by 1939.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] In 1908 A Harvey & Co of St John's, Newfoundland ordered a pair of ships from shipbuilders in Glasgow, Scotland.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] D&W Henderson Ltd built *Bellaventure*, launching her on 23 November 1908.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] Napier and Miller built her sister ship *Bonaventure*, launching her on 5 December 1908.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] Both ships were completed in January 1909.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] On 2 April 1914 *Bellaventure*, commanded by Captain Isaac Randell, was off the northern coast of Newfoundland taking part in a seal hunt.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] 132 hunters from another steamship, *Newfoundland*, had become lost in a storm on an ice floe.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] After 54 hours *Bellaventure* rescued the survivors and recovered 77 dead bodies.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] John's, Newfoundland, with her flags at half mast.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] In 1917 the Russian government bought both *Bellaventure* and *Bonaventure*.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] In 1919, in the North Russia intervention in the Russian Civil War, United Kingdom forces in Arkhangelsk took control of both ships, and Ellerman's Wilson Line was appointed to manage *Bellaventure*.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] Eventually the two ships were renamed *Alexander Sibiryakov* and *Vladimir Rusanov*, after two Russian arctic explorers.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] On 24 November 1936 *Alexander Sibiryakov* was stranded near Cape Menshikov in the Kara Sea.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] She was refloated on 25 December 1936 and returned to service in June 1938.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] In September 1941 the Soviet Navy requisitioned *Alexander Sibiryakov*.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] She continued in service, commanded by Captain Anatoli Kacharava.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] She was defensively armed, at first with several 76 mm (3 in) and 45 mm (2 in) guns.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] By 1942 one 4 in (102 mm) gun had been added.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] On 25 August 1942 during Operation Wunderland the Kriegsmarine heavy cruiser *Admiral Scheer* attacked her off the northwest shore of Russky Island in the Nordenskiöld Archipelago.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] Despite being heavily outgunned, *Alexander Sibiryakov* managed to defend herself for an hour before *Admiral Scheer* sank her.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] *Alexander Sibiryakov* also sent a wireless telegraph signal that warned east and west bound Allied convoys of the attacks, enabling them to avoid the area.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] Most members of *Alexander Sibiryakov*'s crew were killed either in battle or when she sank.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] *Admiral Scheer* captured 22, including severely wounded Captain Kacharava.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] One crewman, stoker Pavel Vavilov, managed to reach Beluha Island and was rescued by a Soviet ship 34 or 35 days later.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] Due to the genocidal Nazi policies towards captured Soviet POWs, only 15 crew members survived the war.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] Soviet sources say 79 killed, 19 taken as prisoners of war, and only 13 of them survived captivity.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] The Soviet Union later sent several expedition to locate the wreck of the ship, including one in 1982, but none had achieved success.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] It was finally located in 2014 by a research expedition organized by a Russian private company 'Fertoing', and in 2015 the wreck was explored by a remotely operated underwater vehicle and divers, who collected some of the ship's parts as museum exhibits.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] A memorial plaque was affixed to the ship's hull in memory of the perished sailors.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] On April 29, 1961, a Decree of the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet of the USSR awarded a number of crew members of the Alexander Sibiryakov "for the courage and fortitude shown by the crew members of the Order of the Red Banner icebreaker steamship *A.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] Kacharava, being awarded the Order of the Red Banner.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] Long before this, even during the war years, a tradition had developed of ships lowering their flags and sounding their horns in salute when passing through this location.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] In 1945, the name *Sibiryakov* was given to the Finnish icebreaker *Jääkarhu* (built 1926), received from Finland as war reparations.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] In honor of the icebreaker's crew, a strait in the Kara Sea north of Dikson Island was named the Sibiryakovtsev Strait.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] The ship's name is also borne by a shoal in the Barents Sea near Novaya Zemlya and a mountain in Antarctica on Enderby Land.
[src:george-w-melville/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] On Belukha Island (Elimelakh Island), a lighthouse was erected in memory of the ship's feat.
[src:george-w-melville/aaron-sachs-historian] He graduated from Harvard University in 1992 with a B.A. in history and literature, and from Yale University, with a Ph.D. in American Studies, in 2004.
[src:george-w-melville/aaron-sachs-historian] He currently is Professor of History and American Studies at Cornell University in Ithaca, New York.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Born in the Grand Duchy of Finland in the Russian Empire, he was forced to move to Sweden in 1857 due to his political activity, where he became a member of the Parliament of Sweden and of the Swedish Academy.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] He led the *Vega* Expedition along the northern coast of Eurasia in 1878–1879.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] This was the first complete crossing of the Northeast Passage.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Initially a troubled enterprise, the successful expedition is considered to be among the highest achievements in the history of Swedish science.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] The Nordenskiölds were an old Fenno-Swedish family, and members of the nobility.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Nordenskiöld's father, Nils Gustaf Nordenskiöld, was a Finnish mineralogist, civil servant and traveller.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] He was also a member of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Adolf Erik was the father of Gustaf Nordenskiöld (explorer of Mesa Verde) and Erland Nordenskiöld (ethnographer of South America) and maternal uncle of Nils Otto Gustaf Nordenskjöld (another polar explorer).
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Nils Otto Gustaf Nordenskjöld's parents were cousins — Otto Gustaf Nordenskjöld (born in 1831 in Hässleby, Sweden) and Anna Elisabet Sofia Nordenskiöld (born in 1841 in Finland), who was the sister of Adolf Erik Nordenskiöld.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] The Swedish side of the family used the spelling "Nordenskjöld", whereas the Finnish side of the family used the "Nordenskiöld" spelling.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] His nephew Erik Nordenskiöld became a zoologist and historian of biology.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Nordenskiöld was born in 1832 in Helsinki, the capital of Finland, but he spent his early youth on the family estate, the Frugård Manor, located in the Numminen village in Mäntsälä.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] He went to school in Porvoo, a small town on the south coast of Finland.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] He then entered the Imperial Alexander University in Helsinki in 1849 where he studied mathematics, geology, and applied himself especially to chemistry and mineralogy.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] He received his master's degree in 1853.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Two years later he published his doctoral dissertation, entitled *"Om grafitens och chondroditens kristallformer"* ("On the crystal forms of graphite and chondrodite").
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Upon his graduation, in 1853, Nordenskiöld accompanied his father to the Ural Mountains and studied the iron and copper mines at Tagilsk; on his return he received minor appointments both at the university and the mining office.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Having studied under Johan Ludvig Runeberg, Nordenskiöld belonged to Liberal, anti-tsarist circles that agitated for Finland's liberation from Russia by the Swedes during the Crimean War.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] An unguarded speech at a convivial entertainment in 1855 drew the attention of the Imperial Russian authorities to his political views, and led to a dismissal from the university.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] He then visited Berlin, continuing his mineralogical studies, and in 1856 obtained a travelling stipend from the university in Helsinki and planned to expend it in geological research in Siberia and Kamchatka.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] In 1856, Nordenskiöld was also appointed Docent in Mineralogy at the university.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] In 1857 he aroused the suspicion of the authorities again, so that he was forced to leave Finland, practically as a political refugee, and was deprived of the right of ever holding office in the university of Finland.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] In 1862, he was one of the founding members of Sällskapet Idun, a men's association founded in Stockholm.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] In 1863 he married Anna Maria Mannerheim, the aunt of Marshal C.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Nordenskiöld settled in Stockholm, and soon he received an offer from Otto Torell, a geologist, to accompany him on an expedition to Spitsbergen.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] He was also awarded the 1869 Royal Geographical Society's Founder's Medal.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Nordenskiöld's participation in three geological expeditions to Spitsbergen, followed by longer Arctic explorations in 1867, 1870, 1872 and 1875, led him to attempt the discovery of the long-sought Northeast Passage.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] This he accomplished in the voyage of the *SS Vega*, navigating for the first time the northern coasts of Europe and Asia.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Starting from Karlskrona on 22 June 1878, the *Vega* doubled Cape Chelyuskin in the following August, and after being frozen in at the end of September near the Bering Strait, completed the voyage successfully in the following summer.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] He edited a monumental record of the expedition in five volumes, and himself wrote a more popular summary in two volumes.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] On his return to Sweden he received an enthusiastic welcome, and in April 1880 was made a baron and a commander of the Order of the North Star.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] In 1883, he visited the east coast of Greenland for the second time, and succeeded in taking his ship through the great ice barrier, a feat attempted in vain during more than three centuries.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] The captain on the *Vega* expedition, Louis Palander, was made a nobleman at the same time, and took the name *Palander af Vega*.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] In 1893, Nordenskiöld was elected to the 12th chair of the Swedish Academy.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] In 1900 he received the Murchison Medal from the Geological Society of London.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] He was nominated for the first Nobel Prize in Physics but died before the prizes were awarded.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Nordenskiöld died on 12 August 1901, in Dalbyö, Södermanland, Sweden, at the age of 68.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] As an explorer, Nordenskiöld was interested in the history of Arctic exploration, especially as evidenced in old maps.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] This interest in turn led him to collect and systematically study early maps.
[src:george-w-melville/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] He left his huge personal collection of early maps to the University of Helsinki, and it was inscribed on UNESCO's Memory of the World International Register in 1997.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] Founded as an engineering society focused on mechanical engineering in North America, ASME is today multidisciplinary and global.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] ASME has over 85,000 members in more than 135 countries worldwide.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] ASME was founded in 1880 in response to numerous steam boiler pressure vessel failures by Alexander Lyman Holley, Henry Rossiter Worthington, John Edison Sweet and Matthias N.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] Forney, with Robert Henry Thurston as the society's founding president.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] Known for setting codes and standards for mechanical devices, ASME conducts one of the world's largest technical publishing operations.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] It holds numerous technical conferences and hundreds of professional development courses each year and sponsors numerous outreach and educational programs.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] Ned Djilali and Georgia Tech president and woman engineer supporter Blake R Van Leer were executive members.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] Kate Gleason and Lydia Weld were the first two women members.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] ASME is one of the oldest standards-developing organizations in America.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] It produces approximately 600 codes and standards covering many technical areas, such as fasteners, plumbing fixtures, elevators, pipelines, and power plant systems and components.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] ASME's standards are developed by committees of subject matter experts using an open, consensus-based process.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] Many ASME standards are cited by government agencies as tools to meet their regulatory objectives.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] ASME standards are therefore voluntary, unless the standards have been incorporated into a legally binding business contract or incorporated into regulations enforced by an authority having jurisdiction, such as a federal, state, or local government agency.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] ASME's standards are used in more than 100 countries and have been translated into numerous languages.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] The largest ASME standard, both in size and in the number of volunteers involved in its preparation, is the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code (BPVC).
[src:george-w-melville/asme] The BPVC provides rules for the design, fabrication, installation, inspection, care, and use of boilers, pressure vessels, and nuclear components.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] The code also includes standards on materials, welding and brazing procedures and qualifications, nondestructive examination, and nuclear in-service inspection.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] In addition to academic journals, since 1880 the ASME has also published the magazine *Mechanical Engineering*.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] This means the nominees need not be professional educators.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] (1879–1964), an ASME Member and professor of mechanical engineering and head of the department at the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn, established the Medal.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] ASME runs several annual E-Fests, or Engineering Festivals, taking the place of the Student Professional Development Conference (SPDC) series.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] In addition to the Human Powered Vehicle Challenge (HPVC), the Innovative Additive Manufacturing 3D Challenge (IAM3D), the Student Design Competition, and the Old Guard Competition, there are also talks, interactive workshops, and entertainment.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] These events allows students to network with working engineers, host contests, and promote ASME's benefits to students as well as professionals.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] E-Fests are held in four regions in the United States and internationally—western U.S, eastern U.S., Asia Pacific, and South America—with the E-Fest location for each region changing every year.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] ASME holds a variety of competitions every year for engineering students from around the world.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] ASME has four key offices in the United States, including its headquarters operation in New York, N.Y., and three international offices in Beijing, China; Brussels, Belgium, and New Delhi, India.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] ASME has two institutes and 32 technical divisions within its organizational structure.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] In 1982, ASME was found to be the first non-profit organization to in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:george-w-melville/asme] The United States Supreme Court found the organization liable for more than $6 million in *American Society of Mechanical Engineers v.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] Navy in 1861 and served as an engineer during the American Civil War.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] He was a member of three Arctic expeditions: a rescue operation aboard the USS *Tigress* in search of the lost Polaris expedition in 1873, the ill-fated Jeannette expedition in 1879, and aboard the USS *Thetis* in search of the Lady Franklin Bay expedition in 1884.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] During the Jeannette expedition, in search of the Open Polar Sea, *Jeannette* became icebound and was eventually crushed.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] Melville was one of the 13 survivors from the thirty-three men that began the expedition.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] The United States Congress awarded Melville the Congressional Gold Jeannette Medal for his gallantry and resourcefulness.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] He published a book in 1884 titled *In the Lena Delta*, about his experiences on the Jeanette expedition.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] He was promoted to engineer in chief of the Navy in 1881, where he reformed the service and increased the professional status of Navy engineers.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] He established an engineering experimental station near the United States Naval Academy in Annapolis to test machinery and equipment before its installation in Navy ships as well as to aid in training engineering officers.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] He served as chief of the Bureau of Steam Engineering from 1887 to 1903 and was promoted to rear admiral in 1889.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] He oversaw the design of 120 ships and introduced innovations including the water-tube boiler, the triple-screw propulsion system, vertical engines, the floating repair ship, and the distilling ship.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] Melville was born in New York City on January 10, 1841, the son of Alexander Melville, a chemist, and Sarah Wallace.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] He was educated at the School of the Christian Brothers, a religious academy, where he studied mathematics, and at the Brooklyn Collegiate and Polytechnic Institute.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] Navy on July 29, 1861, and became an officer of the engineer corps, with the rank of third assistant engineer.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] His first year afloat was spent on the Great Lakes' gunboat *Michigan*, during which time he was promoted to second assistant engineer.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] Melville served in the sloops of war *Dacotah* and *Wachusett* from mid-1862 until late in 1864, taking part in the capture of CSS *Florida* in October 1864.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] He finished the Civil War in the Hampton Roads, Virginia, area working with torpedo boats and as an engineer on the gunboat *Maumee*.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] After the war was over, First Assistant Engineer Melville served aboard several ships, among them the experimental cruiser *Chattanooga*, gunboat *Tacony*, steam sloop *Lancaster* and Asiatic Squadron flagship *Tennessee*.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] For the remainder of his life, Melville belonged to the Military Order of the Loyal Legion of the United States, serving as national commander-in-chief of the Loyal Legion from 1911 to 1912.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] In 1867, Melville married Henrietta Beatty Waldron of Buffalo.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] In 1873, he volunteered for duty as chief engineer of USS *Tigress* for her rescue in Baffin Bay of 19 survivors of the *Polaris* expedition to the Arctic.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] In the summer of 1879, he volunteered for the Jeanette expedition under Lieutenant Commander George W.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] De Long and left San Francisco aboard USS *Jeannette* on August 7, 1879, to try to find a way to the North Pole via the Bering Strait.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] *Jeannette* became icebound in the Chukchi Sea off of Herald Island.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] After two years of effort to save her, *Jeanette* was crushed by the ice and sank June 12, 1881 – leaving the crew stranded on the ice floes in mid-ocean in three small boats and with scant provisions.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] Melville was the only boat commander to find safety in the Lena Delta in Siberia.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] He and his boatmates were rescued by Tungusic hunters.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] Four months later, he mustered a rescue team in search of De Long and his men only to find them dead.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] However, he was able to recover and bring back the ships' logbooks which contained the records of the expedition.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] The logbooks are currently maintained at the U.S.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] The third boat, under the command of Charles W.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] Chipp, was never found and Chipp and seven other men were presumed dead.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] The United States Congress rewarded Melville for his gallantry and resourcefulness by advancing him 15 numbers on the promotion list and awarded him the gold Jeannette Medal.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] He published his experiences and hardships of the expedition in his book, *In the Lena Delta*, published in 1884.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] Melville was promoted to the rank of chief engineer during his time in *Jeannette* and returned to the Arctic in USS *Thetis* in 1884, for the Lady Franklin Bay Expedition in search of the survivors of an Arctic expedition commanded by Army Lieutenant Adolphus Greely.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] He obtained the rank of chief engineer in 1881.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] He served as Inspector of Coal in 1884–1886, then performed his final seagoing duty in the new cruiser *Atlanta*.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] President Grover Cleveland appointed Melville Chief of the Bureau of Steam Engineering August 9, 1887, with the relative rank of commodore.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] During more than a decade and a half in that post, he was responsible for the Navy's propulsion systems during an era of remarkable force expansion, technological progress and institutional change.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] Melville superintended the design of 120 ships of the "New Navy".
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] Among the major technical innovations that he helped introduce, often in defiance of the conservative opinion within the naval establishment, were the water-tube boiler, the triple-screw propulsion system, vertical engines, the floating repair ship, and the distilling ship.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] He was promoted to rear admiral March 3, 1899.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] Melville entirely reformed the service, putting Navy engineers on a professional rather than an artisan footing.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] The Annapolis laboratory was a brainchild of Melville.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] As engineer-in-chief of the Navy, he fought hard to get an appropriation of $400,000 for an experiment and testing laboratory to be located at Annapolis.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] In 1903, he finally was successful in obtaining the appropriation for the engineering experiment station.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] His primary argument for the establishment of an experiment station was that it would increase the efficiency of the Navy.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] His idea was to establish a dependable means for testing—before installation—machinery and equipment designed for Navy ships.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] His secondary argument was that it could aid in training engineering officers and accordingly should be located in Annapolis near the Naval Academy.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] Prior to his retirement, Melville headed a committee tasked with studying how to use fuel oil in Navy boilers instead of coal.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] They strongly recommended that a testing plant be developed to test methods of burning fuel in Navy boilers.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] He retired from active duty on January 10, 1903, and spent his final years in Philadelphia, where he continued to be engaged in matters relating to his profession.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] His first wife having died in 1882, Melville married Estella Smith Polis in 1907.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] Melville was the recipient of many honors during his lifetime, both in the United States and internationally.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] He was one of the 33 founding members of the National Geographic Society.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] He died in Philadelphia on March 17, 1912, and was interred at Laurel Hill Cemetery.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] Melville was a companion of the District of Columbia Commandery of the Naval Order of the United States – a military society of naval officers and their descendants.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] In 1886, he became a companion of the Pennsylvania Commandery of the Military Order of the Loyal Legion of the United States and served as its commander from 1908 to 1909 and also served as national commander-in-chief of the Order from 1911 to 1912.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] He was a member of the Grand Army of the Republic and an honorary member of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers and served as its 18th president.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] He was also an elected member of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] Navy has named two ships in his honor: the destroyer tender USS *Melville* and the oceanographic research ship USNS *Melville*.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] Melville, Montana was named in his honor in 1877.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] Melville Award recognizes outstanding engineering contributions in the applications of knowledge toward research and development of materials, devices, and systems or methods; including design, development, and integration of prototypes and new processes.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] The Melville Medal is awarded periodically by the American Society of Mechanical Engineers in honor of the best original paper from its transactions.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] Melville Hall, built in 1937 on the campus of the United States Naval Academy, was used as classroom and laboratory space for the steam and electrical engineering departments.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] The hall was razed in 1982 to make way for the Academy’s Alumni Hall.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] Melville's name lives on as the new hall's Melville Entrance.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] A statue of Admiral Melville in Navy Park at the Philadelphia Naval Shipyard was created by Samuel Murray.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] The Melville Glacier and Melville Land in Greenland were named after him by Robert Peary.
[src:george-w-melville/george-w-melville] Melville was the subject of a portrait painted by Thomas Eakins in 1897.
